        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-27T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-27T02:00:00-05:00" n="14"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d14">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 PW/1–2745: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-27T14:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 27, 1945—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 27—12:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>122. Following summary of M[ilitary] A[ttaché]’s review week ending 27th: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Jap drive in Southeast China intensified with advances made on all
                            sectors against slight ineffective opposition. Thrust from dialing
                            reached Chikou—12 miles from U. S. airbase at Suichuan which has been
                            demolished. Triple drive from Taohsien reached Leiyang (Hunan) and
                            Pingshih and Loch’eng on railroad. Advance from Chingyuan (Kwangtung)
                            moved north along railway reaching outskirts of Kukong. Enemy now
                            controls all of Hankow–Canton Railroad except small stretch between
                            North Leiyang and Pingshih. In Canton area Japs drove eastward from Polo
                            to Nienshan on Bias Bay. Enemy positions along coast further
                            strengthened.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Fourteenth<note n="49" xml:id="d14fn49">14th U. S. Air Force.</note>
                            and CAC [<hi rend="italic">CACW</hi>]<note n="50" xml:id="d14fn50"
                                >Chinese-American Composite Wing.</note> continued effective aerial
                            offensive despite unfavorable weather which hindered operations.
                            Considerable destruction of locomotives [and] rolling stock reported
                            along Pinghan and Nanking–Tientsin Railways by plane from Sian.
                            Extensive damage to enemy shipping caused in attacks on Yangtze,
                            Tungting Lake and [Yellow?] River areas. Enemy troop movements in
                            Indo-China hindered by 14th operations against bridges [and] railroads.
                            Anti-aircraft opposition all areas light to moderate; fighter opposition
                            weak.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
